// Accept (#2400 resource-wrapper collision, now qualified): two imported
// modules each define a DISTINCT type named `Server` with an
// `impl ServerMethods for Server` block. Both are close resources, so both
// used to lower `Server::close` under one unqualified raw-MIR name and collide
// on a single compilation unit — the historical #2400 duplicate-symbol
// fail-closed case.
//
// The free->close migration qualifies colliding imported resource wrappers, so
// http and websocket `Server::close` now lower to distinct module-qualified
// symbols and both bodies coexist. This program compiles to native and runs;
// full LLVM verification passing is the anti-fail-open guard — a silent
// linkonce merge or a dropped body would surface as the "Global is external,
// but doesn't have external or weak linkage!" verifier dump instead. The
// compiler still fails closed for genuinely-unqualifiable same-name collisions.
import std::net::http;

import std::net::websocket;

fn main() {
    let http_server = http.listen(":0");
    http_server.close();
    let ws_server = websocket.listen(":0");
    ws_server.close();
}
